---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import PageHeader from "../components/PageHeader.astro";
import { siteConfig } from "../lib/site";
import { cvProfile } from "../data/cv";

/*
 * /group — for SDSU Astronomy students deciding whether to work with me.
 *
 * Written as a THRESHOLD, not an advertisement. The previous version stated no
 * eligibility and ended in a bare "Email me" button — a zero-friction
 * invitation to everyone, which drew mail from people I cannot advise. Two
 * things filter now, neither of them a scolding: eligibility stated plainly in
 * the lede, and an email that asks for three specifics only a reader of this
 * page can supply.
 *
 * The links out to /explore, /software and the package docs are part of that
 * mechanism rather than decoration: they give a reader something to DO before
 * writing, which is what separates a prepared student from a mass email.
 */

/** Prefilled so the tag is already there for anyone who follows the page. */
const mailto = `mailto:${siteConfig.email}?subject=${encodeURIComponent("SDSU-ASTRO: ")}`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Group & Opportunities — Anna Rosen, Ph.D."
  description="Research projects for SDSU Astronomy undergraduate and Master's students: differentiable software turns big questions into focused projects a student can own end to end."
  path="/group"
>
  <PageHeader eyebrow="Group & Opportunities" title="A question you can actually finish">
    <Fragment slot="lede">
      I advise <strong>SDSU Astronomy undergraduate and Master's students</strong>.
      Differentiable, modular software turns a big question into a focused one — so
      you can own a real project end to end rather than hold a corner of someone
      else's.
    </Fragment>
  </PageHeader>

  <section class="wrap gr-section" aria-labelledby="work-heading">
    <h2 id="work-heading" class="gr-title">What you'd work on</h2>
    <div class="prose gr-prose">
      <p>
        The Jaxstro ecosystem is deliberately modular. Because each package owns
        one scientific stage and exposes clean, differentiable interfaces, a
        single well-scoped question — a new IMF prescription, a dynamical
        benchmark, a survey systematic, an identifiability test — becomes a
        self-contained project with a beginning and an end.
      </p>
      <p>
        That is the point: many compact, finishable contributions rather than a
        few monolithic ones, on tools you can actually read.
      </p>
      {/* Explicit {" "} before every inline element that follows a line break:
          Astro collapses that whitespace, which silently produced
          "thejaxstro andprogenaxdocumentation" here. */}
      <p class="gr-start">
        <strong>Where to start looking:</strong>{" "}
        <a href="/explore">the explorables</a> to see the models running,{" "}
        <a href="/software">the software</a> for what each package does, and the{" "}
        <a href="https://jaxstro.github.io/jaxstro/" rel="noopener">jaxstro</a> and{" "}
        <a href="https://jaxstro.github.io/progenax/" rel="noopener">progenax</a>{" "}
        documentation if you want to read the interfaces themselves.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="wrap gr-section" aria-labelledby="interests-heading">
    <h2 id="interests-heading" class="gr-title">Research interests</h2>
    <ul class="gr-tags" role="list">
      {cvProfile.interests.map((i) => <li class="gr-tag">{i}</li>)}
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="wrap gr-section" aria-labelledby="skills-heading">
    <h2 id="skills-heading" class="gr-title">Recommended skills</h2>
    <div class="prose gr-prose">
      <p>
        None of this is a checklist you must clear before talking to me. It is
        what makes the first month go well.
      </p>
    </div>
    <ul class="gr-skills" role="list">
      <li>
        You can <strong>write and debug your own Python</strong> — not only run
        someone else's notebook.
      </li>
      <li>
        You are comfortable thinking in arrays: NumPy, or the willingness to learn
        it quickly.
      </li>
      <li>A terminal and <code>git</code>, or no fear of picking them up.</li>
      <li>
        <span class="gr-skills__soft">Helpful, not required:</span> JAX, matplotlib,
        LaTeX, any experience on a cluster.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div class="prose gr-prose">
      {/* Deliberately no "if you took course X you're ready" line: naming
          specific courses ties the page to a teaching schedule that changes,
          and the COMP courses are rarely taken by Astronomy students anyway. */}
      <p>
        You do <strong>not</strong> need prior research experience, and you do not
        need astrophysics beyond the introductory sequence. If you have written
        code for a class or a project and had to make it actually work, that is
        the relevant experience.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="wrap gr-section" aria-labelledby="email-heading">
    <h2 id="email-heading" class="gr-title">Before you email me</h2>
    <div class="prose gr-prose">
      <p>
        Have a look around first, then tell me three things. Two or three sentences
        each is plenty — I'm not looking for a polished proposal, I'm looking for
        evidence that something specific here caught your interest.
      </p>
    </div>
    <ol class="gr-ask" role="list">
      <li>
        <strong>Which package or question</strong> you'd like to work on, and what
        drew you to it.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Where you are</strong>: your year, your major, and which of my
        courses you've taken, if any.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>One thing you'd want to try</strong> — a plot you'd make, a test
        you'd run, a number you'd check. It doesn't have to be right.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p class="gr-tag-note">
      Please put <code>SDSU-ASTRO</code> in the subject line.
    </p>
    <p class="gr-cta">
      <a class="gr-btn" href={mailto}>Email me →</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="wrap gr-section" aria-labelledby="collab-heading">
    <h2 id="collab-heading" class="gr-title">Potential collaborators</h2>
    <div class="prose gr-prose">
      <p>
        The software is open and built to be extended. If you work on star
        clusters, stellar populations, or survey inference and want to run new
        models, test a prescription against your own, or design an observing
        program around what these models predict, I'd like to hear from you — the
        three items above don't apply.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .gr-section {
    padding-block: var(--space-l) var(--space-xl);
  }
  .gr-title {
    font-size: var(--step-2);
    padding-block-end: var(--space-2xs);
    margin-block-end: var(--space-m);
    border-block-end: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .gr-prose p {
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    margin-block-end: var(--space-s);
  }
  .gr-prose code,
  .gr-skills code,
  .gr-tag-note code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--step--1);
    color: var(--spec-teal-bright);
  }
  .gr-start {
    padding-block-start: var(--space-2xs);
  }

  .gr-tags {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: var(--space-2xs) var(--space-s);
  }
  .gr-tag {
    padding: var(--space-3xs) var(--space-s);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--step--1);
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    background: var(--bg-deep);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 999px;
  }

  /* Both lists keep the prose measure, so each section reads as one argument
     rather than a form to fill in. */
  .gr-skills,
  .gr-ask {
    max-inline-size: var(--width-prose);
    display: grid;
    gap: var(--space-2xs);
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    margin-block-end: var(--space-m);
  }
  .gr-skills {
    list-style: none;
    padding-inline-start: 0;
  }
  .gr-skills li {
    position: relative;
    padding-inline-start: var(--space-m);
  }
  .gr-skills li::before {
    content: "";
    position: absolute;
    inset-inline-start: 0;
    inset-block-start: 0.62em;
    inline-size: 6px;
    block-size: 6px;
    border-radius: 999px;
    background: var(--spec-teal-bright);
  }
  .gr-skills__soft {
    color: var(--ink-dim);
  }
  .gr-ask {
    padding-inline-start: var(--space-m);
  }
  .gr-ask li::marker {
    color: var(--spec-cyan);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
  }
  .gr-ask strong,
  .gr-skills strong {
    color: var(--ink);
  }

  .gr-tag-note {
    max-inline-size: var(--width-prose);
    color: var(--ink-soft);
  }

  .gr-cta {
    margin-block-start: var(--space-m);
  }
  .gr-btn {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: var(--space-2xs) var(--space-m);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--step--1);
    color: var(--ink);
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--border-strong);
    border-radius: 999px;
    transition: border-color var(--dur-fast) var(--ease-out);
  }
  .gr-btn:hover {
    border-color: var(--spec-teal-bright);
    color: var(--spec-teal-bright);
  }
</style>
